Problem 3 (40 points)

In this problem you will practice some basic R operations. Include solutions to each items by inserting a new R chunk of code (make sure you run the chunk so that the output is displayed)

  1. Create a variable called my_name that contains your preferred name.
my_name <- "Christian"
print(my_name)
[1] "Christian"
  1. Create a variable called name_length that holds how many letters are in my_name.
name_length <- nchar(my_name, type = "chars")
print(name_length)
[1] 9
  1. Show which value is bigger: \(e^\pi\) or \(\pi^e\).
e <- (1 + 1/100)^100
x <- c(e^pi,pi^e)
print(x)
[1] 22.78241 22.11556
max(x)
[1] 22.78241
  1. Define a function called add_three that takes a single argument and returns a value 3 units larger than the input.
# Creates the function add_tree that multiplies an input by 3
add_three <- function() {
  t <- as.integer(readline(prompt = "_ + 3 ="))
  print(paste(t,"+ 3 ="))
  t <- t+3
  print(t)
}
add_three()
5
[1] "5 + 3 ="
[1] 8
  1. Use the colon operator : to create a vector v of numbers from 10 to 49. Find the length of this vector using the length() function.
v <- (10:49)
length(v)
[1] 40
  1. Use the seq() function to produce a range of number from -5 to 10 in 0.5 increments.
seq(-5,10,0.5)
